    <subsection xml:id="Question_3_1_3">
    <title> Problem 3</title>
    <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
            
            <p>
                Any integer is of one of the following forms:
                <md>
                    <mrow> 6k+0 \amp = 3(3k)+0</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+1 \amp = 3(2k)+1</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+2 \amp = 3(2k)+2</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+3 \amp = 3(2k+1)+0</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+4 \amp = 3(2k+1)+1</mrow>
                    <mrow> 6k+5 \amp = 3(2k+1)+2.</mrow>
                </md>

                So, if an integer is of the form <m>3n+1</m>, then it is either of the form <m>6k+1</m> or <m>6k+4</m>. An integer of the form <m>6k+4=2(3k+2)</m> is never prime so a prime of the form <m>3n+1</m> must also of the form <m>6m+1</m>.
                
               
            </p>

            <p>
                Or:
                Except for <m>p=2</m> and <m>p=3</m> all primes are congruent to either <m>1</m>   or <m>5</m> modulo 6. If <m>p \equiv 5 \pmod{6}</m>, then <m>p\equiv  2\pmod{3}.</m> So, all primes <m>p\equiv 1 \pmod{3}</m> must be <m>p\equiv 1 \pmod{6}.</m>
            </p>
        
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                All primes are of the form <m>3k+1</m> or <m>3k+2</m>.  Suppose an integer, <m>w</m>, is of the form <m>3n+2</m> and that all of its prime factors are of the form <m>3k+1</m>. That is:
                <md>
                    w=(3k_1+1)(3k_2+1)\cdots(3k_q+1).
                </md>
                
                Expand the right hand side to see that 
                <md>
                    2=3(\text{ some integer })+1
                </md>
                which contradicts <m>w</m> being of the form <m>3n+2</m>.  Thus <m>w</m> must have at least one prime factor of the form <m>3n+2</m>. 
                

            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            
            <p>
                Let <m>p</m> be prime and suppose <m>3p+1=k^2</m> for some integer <m>k</m>. Then <md>
                    3p=k^2-1=(k-1)(k+1).
                </md>
                By the FTA <m>3=k-1</m> and <m>p=k+1</m>.  This has only one solution: <m>k=4</m> and hence <m>p=5.</m>
                
            </p>
        
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>p</m> is prime and <md>
                    p=n^2-4=(n-2)(n+2)
                </md>
                then <m>n-2=1</m> so <m>n=3</m>, and <m>p=5.</m>
                    
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                   
               
                
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="Question_3_1_5">
    <title> Problem 5</title>
    <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
            <!--
            <p>
                Write the prime factorization of <m>a</m>: <md>a=p_1^{e_1}\cdots p_m^{e_m}.</md>
                Then <md>
                    a^n=p_1^{ne_1}\cdots p_m^{ne_m}.
                </md>
                If <m>p|a^n</m> then (wlog) <m>p=p_1</m> and <m>p_1^n |a^n.</m>
            </p>
        -->
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Write out prime factorizations:
             <md>
                <mrow> a \amp= p\cdot q_1^{e_1}q_2^{e_2}\cdots q_k^{e_k} </mrow>
                <mrow> b \amp = p \cdot w_1^{f_1}w_2^{f_2}\cdots w_l^{f_l} </mrow>
             </md> 
             where <m>p, q_i, w_j</m> are all prime.  None of the <m>q</m>s are equal to the <m>w</m>s. One of the <m>q</m>s or one of the <m>w</m>s may equal <m>p</m> BUT not both.  (otherwise <m>\text{gcd}(a,b)</m> would be greater than <m>p</m>.)
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, 
<md>
                <mrow> a^2 \amp= p^2\cdot q_1^{2e_1}q_2^{2e_2}\cdots q_k^{2e_k} </mrow>
                <mrow> b^2 \amp = p^2 \cdot w_1^{2f_1}w_2^{2f_2}\cdots w_l^{2f_l} </mrow>
             </md> 

             from which we see that <m>\text{gcd}(a^2, b^2)=p^2.</m>

            The others are similar.  The answers are: <m>p</m>, and <m>p^2.</m>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="Question_3_1_6">
    <title> Problem 6</title>
    <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
            <p>
                
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                First notice for <m>n=4</m> <m>4 \nmid 3!</m>.

                Let <m>p|n</m>. Since <m>n</m> is composite <m>p &lt; n</m>. Let <m>p^\alpha</m> be the highest power of <m>p</m> that divides <m>n</m>. That is <m>p^\alpha|n</m> and <m>p^{\alpha+1} \nmid n</m>. Then <m>(n-1)!</m> contains factors of <m>p, p^2, \dots p^{\alpha-1}.</m>. (It may also contain a factor of <m>p^\alpha</m>, but not if <m>n=p^\alpha</m>.) So 
                <md>
                    p\cdot p^2 \cdots p^{\alpha-1}|(n-1)!
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="Question_3_1_15">
    <title> Problem 15</title>
    <p>
        If <m>a</m> is a square, then <m>a=k^2</m>.  Write the canonical form of <m>k</m>:
        <md>
            k=p_1^{e_1}\cdot p_t^{e_t}.
        </md>
        Then 
        <md>
            a=k^2=p_1^{2e_1}\cdot p_t^{2e_t}.
        </md>
        Conversely if 
        <md>
            a=p_1^{2f_1}\cdots p_t^{2f_t}
        </md>
        then <m>a</m> is a square:

        <md>
            a=(p_1^{f_1}\cdots p_t^{f_t})^2.
        </md>
        
    </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="Question_3_1_16">
    <title> Problem 16</title>
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
    <p>
        If an integer ,<m>n</m>, cannot be factored into <em>distinct</em> primes, then its prime factorization contains at least one prime repeated. That is, there is some prime <m>p</m> such that <m>p^2|n</m>. Thus, <m>n</m> is not square free. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Conversely if <m>n</m> is not square free, there is some integer <m>k</m> such that <m>k^2|n</m>. The integer <m>k \neq 1</m> by definition, so there is some prime <m>p</m> such that <m>p|k</m>. Then <m>p^2|k^2</m>, and hence <m>p^2|n</m> so <m>p</m> cannot be factored into <em>distinct</em> primes.
    
    </p> 
</li>
<li>
    <p>
        Follow the hint and use properties of exponent.
    </p>
</li>

</ol>
    </subsection>

